<h3 id="create">Create your digital garden</h3>

<p>If you already have Jekyll on your pc, all you have to do is <strong>make a copy of <a href="https://github.com/crixer18/lilium-digital-garden-jekyll">Lilium template reposiory from GitHub</a></strong> and use it to create a new website.</p>

<p>To make a copy of the repository I suggest you to â€œforkâ€ mine, so you can find the Lilium template in your GitHub account.</p>

<p><img src="/imgs/how-to-1.png" alt="GitHub clone repository" /></p>

<p>In this image you can see my repositoryâ€™s. Yours will be similar but intead of â€œcrixer18/giardinoâ€ there will be your user name and the name of the repository which contains the template.</p>

<p>From there you can clone the repository on your pc using terminal.</p>

<p><img src="/imgs/how-to-2.png" alt="Locally copy a github repository" /></p>

<p>In your case, the link in red will be the one you copied from GitHub repository (previous image). The string in blue is the name of the new folder youâ€™re going to create, in which the template will be downloaded.</p>

<p>At this point, youâ€™ve created the site. You can enter the directory (with $cd my-digital-garden or whatever is the name you chose), and test the Jekyll site on localhost:</p>

<p><img src="/imgs/how-to-3.png" alt="Create Jekyll website" /></p>

<p>Then:</p>

<p><img src="/imgs/how-to-4.png" alt="Locally run Jekyll wbsite" /></p>

<p>Watch the result: open <a href="http://localhost:4000/">localhost:4000</a> in your browser.</p>

<p>It was easy, wasnâ€™t it?</p>

